{"title_page": "John Butler (album)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2010}}\n{{short description|first full length album by the John Butler Trio}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = John Butler\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[The John Butler Trio]]\n| cover      = John_Butler_Self_Titled.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 27 December 1998\n| recorded   = Studio Couch, [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]]\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Traditional music|Roots]]\n| length     = 64:08\n| label      = Independent/[[MGM Distribution]]\n| producer   = [[John Butler (musician)|John Butler]]\n| prev_title = [[Searching for Heritage]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[JBT EP]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n}}\n'''''John Butler''''' is the first full-length album by the [[John Butler Trio]], released 27 December 1998.\n\nIt was recorded at Studio Couch, [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]] and engineered by George Nikoloudis and Shaun O'Callaghan, mixed by Shaun O'Callaghan and George Nikoloudis and mastered by Shaun O'Callaghan and Richard Mahony at Studio Couch and Toad Hall.\n\nAll music and lyrics were written, arranged and produced by [[John Butler (musician)|John Butler]], except for the words of the chorus in \"Colours\" which were from [[Sly and the Family Stone]].<ref name=\"AMG\">{{Cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r876927|pure_url=yes}} |title=John Butler > Credits |publisher=[[All Media Guide]] |work=[[allmusic]] |accessdate=2 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nWith Jason McGann on drums and Gavin Shoesmith on bass, the first version of the group recorded the album in December 1998 which was launched at Mojos Bar in [[North Fremantle, Western Australia|North Fremantle]].\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written and composed by [[John Butler (musician)|John Butler]],<ref name=\"APRA\">{{Cite web|title=Australasian Performing Right Association |publisher=[[Australasian Performing Right Association|APRA]] |url=http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/worksearch.axd?q=Judas |accessdate=2 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306013726/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/worksearch.axd?q=Judas |archivedate= 6 March 2012 }}</ref> except where noted.\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = John Butler\n| total_length    = 64:08\n| title1          = Valley\n| length1         = 8:34\n| title2          = Inspiration\n| length2         = 5:18\n| title3          = Busted\n| length3         = 7:40\n| title4          = Sista\n| length4         = 3:18\n| title5          = Ocean\n| length5         = 12:28\n| title6          = Colours\n| note6           = the words of the chorus are from [[Sly and the Family Stone]]<ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n| length6         = 9:05\n| title7          = Crazy\n| length7         = 5:29\n| title8          = Keeper\n| length8         = 5:00\n| title9          = Under an Indian Sky\n| length9         = 7:39\n}}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Region\n! Date\n! Label\n! Format\n! Catalog\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Australia]]\n| 27 December 1998\n| Independent\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Compact Disc|CD]]\n| JB-002\n|-\n| 13 November 2000\n| [[MGM Distribution]]\n| JBT001\n|-\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n* John Butler - resonator [Dobro] guitar, guitar [11 string], vocals\n* Gavin Shoesmith - bass guitar and double bass\n* Jason McGann - percussion\n\n==Credits==\n* Arrangements, Artwork, Producer - John Butler\n* Artwork [Design, Layout] - Peter Nicol\n* Engineer, Mixer - George Nikoloudis, Shaun O'Callaghan\n* Mastering - Richard Mahony, Shaun O'Callaghan\n* Photography [Disc Pic] - Tony Gajewski\n* Photography [Photos Of John Butler's Art Pieces] - Danny Khoo\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The John Butler Trio}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John Butler (Album)}}\n[[Category:1998 debut albums]]\n[[Category:John Butler Trio albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|first full length album by the John Butler Trio}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = John Butler\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[The John Butler Trio]]\n| cover      = John_Butler_Self_Titled.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 27 December 1998\n| recorded   = Studio Couch, [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]]\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Traditional music|Roots]]\n| length     = 64:08\n| label      = Independent/[[MGM Distribution]]\n| producer   = [[John Butler (musician)|John Butler]]\n| prev_title = [[Searching for Heritage]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[JBT EP]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n}}\n'''''John Butler''''' is the first full-length album by the [[John Butler Trio]], released 27 December 1998.\n\nIt was recorded at Studio Couch, [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]] and engineered by George Nikoloudis and Shaun O'Callaghan, mixed by Shaun O'Callaghan and George Nikoloudis and mastered by Shaun O'Callaghan and Richard Mahony at Studio Couch and Toad Hall.\n\nAll music and lyrics were written, arranged and produced by [[John Butler (musician)|John Butler]], except for the words of the chorus in \"Colours\" which were from [[Sly and the Family Stone]].<ref name=\"AMG\">{{Cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r876927|pure_url=yes}} |title=John Butler > Credits |publisher=[[All Media Guide]] |work=[[allmusic]] |accessdate=2 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nWith Jason McGann on drums and Gavin Shoesmith on bass, the first version of the group recorded the album in December 1998 which was launched at Mojos Bar in [[North Fremantle, Western Australia|North Fremantle]].\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written and composed by [[John Butler (musician)|John Butler]],<ref name=\"APRA\">{{Cite web|title=Australasian Performing Right Association |publisher=[[Australasian Performing Right Association|APRA]] |url=http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/worksearch.axd?q=Judas |accessdate=2 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306013726/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/worksearch.axd?q=Judas |archivedate= 6 March 2012 }}</ref> except where noted.\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = John Butler\n| total_length    = 64:08\n| title1          = Valley\n| length1         = 8:34\n| title2          = Inspiration\n| length2         = 5:18\n| title3          = Busted\n| length3         = 7:40\n| title4          = Sista\n| length4         = 3:18\n| title5          = Ocean\n| length5         = 12:28\n| title6          = Colours\n| note6           = the words of the chorus are from [[Sly and the Family Stone]]<ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n| length6         = 9:05\n| title7          = Crazy\n| length7         = 5:29\n| title8          = Keeper\n| length8         = 5:00\n| title9          = Under an Indian Sky\n| length9         = 7:39\n}}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Region\n! Date\n! Label\n! Format\n! Catalog\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Australia]]\n| 27 December 1998\n| Independent\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Compact Disc|CD]]\n| JB-002\n|-\n| 13 November 2000\n| [[MGM Distribution]]\n| JBT001\n|-\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n* John Butler - resonator [Dobro] guitar, guitar [11 string], vocals\n* Gavin Shoesmith - bass guitar and double bass\n* Jason McGann - percussion\n\n==Credits==\n* Arrangements, Artwork, Producer - John Butler\n* Artwork [Design, Layout] - Peter Nicol\n* Engineer, Mixer - George Nikoloudis, Shaun O'Callaghan\n* Mastering - Richard Mahony, Shaun O'Callaghan\n* Photography [Disc Pic] - Tony Gajewski\n* Photography [Photos Of John Butler's Art Pieces] - Danny Khoo\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The John Butler Trio}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}{{Use British English|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John Butler (Album)}}\n[[Category:1998 debut albums]]\n[[Category:John Butler Trio albums]]\n", "name_user": "Dan arndt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Oz English tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Butler_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Kentucky Public Radio", "text_new": "{{Infobox Broadcasting network\n|name           = Kentucky Public Radio Network(KPRN)\n|logo           = [[Image:Kentucky-Public-Radio.jpg]]\n|type           = [[Public Broadcasting|Public Radio Network]]\n|branding       = \n|airdate        = \n|country        = {{USA}}\n|available      = \n|founded        = \n|founder        =\n|slogan         = \n|motto          = \n|market_share   = \n|license_area   = \n|broadcast_area = {{flag|Kentucky}}\n|area           = \n|erp            = \n|owner          =\n|key_people     = Capital Bureau Chief Ryland Barton\n|foundation     = \n|launch_date    = December 1997\n|dissolved      = \n|former_names   = \n|digital        = \n|analog         = \n|servicename1   = \n|service1       = \n|servicename2   = \n|service2       = \n|servicename3   = \n|service3       = \n|servicename4   = \n|service4       = \n|callsigns      = \n|callsign_meaning = \n|former_callsigns = \n|affiliation    = [[National Public Radio]]\n|affiliates     = [[WEKU]], [[WUKY]], [[WFPL]], [[WKYU-FM|WKYU]], [[WMKY]], [[WKMS]]\n|groups         = \n|former_affiliations = \n|website             = \n|footnotes      = \n}}\n\n'''The Kentucky Public Radio Network''' (KPRN) is a consortium of four [[public radio]] stations: WFPL (Louisville Public Media), WKMS (Murray), WKYU (Bowling Green), WEKU (Richmond/Lexington).\n\nThe primary mission of Kentucky Public Radio is to facilitate content sharing among stations and the hiring and management of a Statehouse Reporter.\n\nKPRN is managed by board of directors composed of the individual station managers. \n\nIn January, 2015 Ryland Barton was named the State Capital Bureau Chief in [[Frankfort, Kentucky]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://louisvillepublicmedia.org/2015/kentucky-public-radio-network-hires-ryland-barton-as-state-capitol-bureau-chief/|title=Kentucky Public Radio Network Hires Ryland Barton as State Capitol Bureau Chief \u2013 Louisville Public Media|website=louisvillepublicmedia.org|access-date=2016-05-22|date=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliates==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Location\n!Frequency\n![[Call sign]]\n!Owner\n|-\n|[[Richmond, Kentucky|Richmond]]\n|88.9 FM\n|'''[[WEKU]]''' \n|[[Eastern Kentucky University]]\n|-\n|[[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]]\n|89.3 FM\n|'''[[WFPL]]''' \n|[[Louisville Public Media]]\n|-\n|[[Bowling Green, Kentucky|Bowling Green]]\n|88.9 FM\n|'''[[WKYU-FM|WKYU]]''' \n|[[WKU Public Radio]]\n|-\n|[[Murray, Kentucky|Murray]]\n|91.3 FM\n|'''[[WKMS]]''' \n|[[Murray State University]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://kentuckypublicradio.org/ Official website]\n\n{{NPR Kentucky}}\n{{American broadcast radio}}\n\n{{coord|38|14|53.7|N|85|45|27.3|W|type:landmark_region:US-KY|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Kentucky|*]]\n[[Category:NPR member networks]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Broadcasting network\n|name           = Kentucky Public Radio Network(KPRN)\n|logo           = [[Image:Kentucky-Public-Radio.jpg]]\n|type           = [[Public Broadcasting|Public Radio Network]]\n|branding       = \n|airdate        = \n|country        = {{USA}}\n|available      = \n|founded        = \n|founder        =\n|slogan         = \n|motto          = \n|market_share   = \n|license_area   = \n|broadcast_area = {{flag|Kentucky}}\n|area           = \n|erp            = \n|owner          =\n|key_people     = Capital Bureau Chief Ryland Barton\n|foundation     = \n|launch_date    = December 1997\n|dissolved      = \n|former_names   = \n|digital        = \n|analog         = \n|servicename1   = \n|service1       = \n|servicename2   = \n|service2       = \n|servicename3   = \n|service3       = \n|servicename4   = \n|service4       = \n|callsigns      = \n|callsign_meaning = \n|former_callsigns = \n|affiliation    = [[National Public Radio]]\n|affiliates     = [[WEKU]], [[WUKY]], [[WFPL]], [[WKYU-FM|WKYU]], [[WMKY]], [[WKMS]]\n|groups         = \n|former_affiliations = \n|website             = \n|footnotes      = \n}}\n\n'''The Kentucky Public Radio Network''' (KPRN) is a consortium of four [[public radio]] stations: WFPL (Louisville Public Media), WKMS (Murray), WKYU (Bowling Green), WEKU (Richmond/Lexington).\n\nThe primary mission of Kentucky Public Radio is to facilitate content sharing among stations and the hiring and management of a Statehouse Reporter.\n\nKPRN is managed by board of directors composed of the individual station managers. \n\nIn January, 2015 Ryland Barton was named the State Capital Bureau Chief in [[Frankfort, Kentucky]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://louisvillepublicmedia.org/2015/kentucky-public-radio-network-hires-ryland-barton-as-state-capitol-bureau-chief/|title=Kentucky Public Radio Network Hires Ryland Barton as State Capitol Bureau Chief \u2013 Louisville Public Media|website=louisvillepublicmedia.org|access-date=2016-05-22|date=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliates==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Location\n!Frequency\n![[Call sign]]\n!Owner\n|-\n|[[Richmond, Kentucky|Richmond]]\n|88.9 FM\n|'''[[WEKU]]''' \n|[[Eastern Kentucky University]]\n|-\n|[[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]]\n|89.3 FM\n|'''[[WFPL]]''' \n|[[Louisville Public Media]]\n|-\n|[[Bowling Green, Kentucky|Bowling Green]]\n|88.9 FM\n|'''[[WKYU-FM|WKYU]]''' \n|[[Western Kentucky University]]\n|-\n|[[Murray, Kentucky|Murray]]\n|91.3 FM\n|'''[[WKMS]]''' \n|[[Murray State University]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://kentuckypublicradio.org/ Official website]\n\n{{NPR Kentucky}}\n{{American broadcast radio}}\n\n{{coord|38|14|53.7|N|85|45|27.3|W|type:landmark_region:US-KY|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Kentucky|*]]\n[[Category:NPR member networks]]\n", "name_user": "Ben76266", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAffiliates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kentucky_Public_Radio"}
{"title_page": "Married to a Lie", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Married to a Lie\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = [[Miniseries]]\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = Marko Leino\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Minna Virtanen]]\n| starring             = [[Laura Birn]]<br />[[Mikko Olavi Nousiainen|Mikko Nousiainen]]<br />[[Antti Luusuaniemi]]<br />[[Elina Stirkkinen]]<br />[[Anna Paavilainen]]<br />[[Jussi Nikkil\u00e4]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = Lauri Porra\n| country              = Finland\n| language             = Finnish\n| num_episodes         = 4\n| producer             = \n| editor               = Kimmo Taavila\n| cinematography       = \n| runtime              = 180 min.\n| company              = \n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = [[MTV3]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2008|12|28}}\n| last_aired           = {{Start date|2009|01|18}}\n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = http://www.vertigo.fi\n}}\n\n'''Married to a Lie'''  is a Finnish television miniseries (4 x 45 min.) produced by [[Vertigo Production]] in 2008.\n\nMarried to a Lie received the award for Best Miniseries of 2009 at the [[Venla]] Finnish Television Awards gala 2010.\n\n==Plot==\nSonja ([[Laura Birn]]) is about to marry Kim ([[Mikko Nousiainen]]). In the middle of the wedding preparations, Kim is suddenly taken ill, Sonja sets off to drive him to the hospital, is involved in a car crash, and Kim dies in the hospital. After she recovers from the worst trauma, Sonja starts to sort out the practicalities connected to Kim\u2019s death. It transpires that Kim had been lying to her about his entire life. The successful businessman turns out to be an unemployed idler, who, to top it all, was going to leave Sonja just before the wedding. The man Sonja was marrying did not exist. Sonja starts to probe into Kim\u2019s hidden past, as it has been her past also. It is the only way for Sonja to survive her loss.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1346786/ IMDb: Married to a Lie]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/Vertigofi/ Vertigo Production YouTube Channel]\n\n[[Category:Finnish drama television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Married to a Lie\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = [[Miniseries]]\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = Marko Leino\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Minna Virtanen]]\n| starring             = [[Laura Birn]]<br />[[Mikko Olavi Nousiainen|Mikko Nousiainen]]<br />[[Antti Luusuaniemi]]<br />[[Elina Stirkkinen]]<br />[[Anna Paavilainen]]<br />[[Jussi Nikkil\u00e4]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = Lauri Porra\n| country              = Finland\n| language             = Finnish\n| num_episodes         = 4\n| producer             = \n| editor               = Kimmo Taavila\n| cinematography       = \n| runtime              = 180 min.\n| company              = \n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = [[MTV3]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2008|12|28}}\n| last_aired           = {{Start date|2009|01|18}}\n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = http://www.vertigo.fi\n}}\n\n'''Married to a Lie'''  is a Finnish television miniseries (4 x 45 min.) produced by [[Vertigo Production]] in 2008.\n\nMarried to a Lie received the award for Best Miniseries of 2009 at the [[Venla]] Finnish Television Awards gala 2010.\n\n==Plot==\nSonja ([[Laura Birn]]) is about to get married to Kim ([[Mikko Nousiainen]]). In the middle of the wedding preparations, Kim is suddenly taken ill, Sonja sets off to drive him to the hospital, is involved in a car crash, and Kim dies in the hospital. After she recovers from the worst trauma, Sonja starts to sort out the practicalities connected to Kim\u2019s death. It transpires that Kim had been lying to her about his entire life. The successful businessman turns out to be an unemployed idler, who, to top it all, was going to leave Sonja just before the wedding. The man Sonja was marrying did not exist. Sonja starts to probe into Kim\u2019s hidden past, as it has been her past also. It is the only way for Sonja to survive her loss.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1346786/ IMDb: Married to a Lie]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/Vertigofi/ Vertigo Production YouTube Channel]\n\n[[Category:Finnish drama television series]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Married_to_a_Lie"}
{"title_page": "Vancouver Rape Relief & Women's Shelter", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n|name         = \n|image        = Vancouver Rape Relief logo.jpeg\n|image_border =\n|size         = 300px\n|map          =\n|msize        =\n|malt         =\n|mcaption     =\n|abbreviation =\n|motto        = \"No woman is free until all women are free.\"\n|formation    = 1973\n|extinction   =\n|type         = [[Rape crisis center]]\n|status       =\n|purpose      =\n|headquarters = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]\n|location     =\n|coords       =\n|region_served = Vancouver\n|membership   =\n|language     =\n|leader_title =\n|leader_name  =\n|main_organ   =\n|parent_organization =\n|affiliations =\n|num_staff    =\n|num_volunteers =\n|budget       =\n|website      = {{URL|http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/}}\n|remarks      =\n}}\n\n'''Vancouver Rape Relief & Women's Shelter''' is Canada's oldest [[rape crisis center]], located in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Steacy |first1=Lisa |title=Opinion: Vancouver Rape Relief stands by women |url=https://vancouversun.com/opinion/vancouver-rape-relief-stands-by-women |work=Vancouver Sun |date=13 April 2016}}</ref> The shelter was established in 1973 and has operated a [[feminist]] [[Transitional living|transition house]] since 1983, offering women shelter from men who are abusing them, including fathers, husbands, sons, [[pimp]]s, johns and landlords.{{efn|\"Since 1973 the Vancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter has been an organizing centre and a 24-hour phone line for women raped and battered. Since 1980, it has also been a feminist transition house. We house women running from abusive men&nbsp;\u2013 usually husbands and fathers, but sometimes pimps, johns, landlords, and sons.\"<ref name=Lakemanp210>{{cite book |last1=Lakeman |first1=Lee |last2=Lee |first2=Alice |last3=Jay |first3=Suzanne |editor1-last=Stark |editor1-first=Christine |editor2-last=Whisnant |editor2-first=Rebecca |editor1-link= |editor2-link= |title=Not for Sale: Feminists Resisting Prostitution and Pornography |date=2004 |publisher=Spinifex Press Pty Ltd. |location=North Melbourne, Victoria |page=210 |chapter=Resisting the promotion of prostitution in Canada: A view from the Vancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter|ref=harv}}</ref>}} A member of the Canadian Association of Sexual Assault Centres (CASAC),{{sfn|Lakeman|Lee|Jay|2004|pp=210\u2013211}} it is an independent, non-governmental group with no connection to the criminal justice system.<ref>{{cite news|title=About Us |url=http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/about |accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n\n==Services==\nThe group operates a 24-hour, confidential, free-of-charge [[crisis hotline]] for abused women. More broadly, it works to eradicate all [[violence against women]], which it defines as including \"[[sexual assault]], [[domestic violence|wife assault]], [[incest]], [[prostitution]], and [[sexual harassment]]\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Give/Get Help |url=http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/givegethelp |accessdate= December 20, 2012}}</ref> According to its website, this mission is accomplished by not only providing housing, education, resources, and support for women, but also by participating in global political struggles around issues of [[Race (human classification)|race]], [[Social class|class]], [[colonialism]], and [[imperialism]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Global Resistance |url=http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/globalresistance |accessdate= December 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nVancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter consists of 27 collective members who work at the shelter, ten of whom are staff. They are committed to having their membership represent Vancouver population and therefore have a third of women identifying as lesbian women, a third are working class women, and almost half of them identify as women of colour. Vancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter have stated publicly that their collective members are themselves survivors of male violence against women, ex-callers calling the line, ex-residents who lived at the shelter, and survivors of prostitution. <ref name=Lakemanp210/>\n\n==''Kimberly Nixon v. Vancouver Rape Relief Society''==\n{{further|Kimberly Nixon Rape Relief Case}}\nIn August 1995 Kimberly Nixon, a [[trans woman]], filed a complaint against the shelter with the [[British Columbia Human Rights Tribunal]] after being turned down for a place on the shelter's training programme for volunteer counselors. Nixon argued that this constituted illegal [[discrimination]] under Section 41 of the [[British Columbia Human Rights Code]]. Vancouver Rape Relief countered that individuals are shaped by the [[socialization]] and experiences of their formative years, and that, having been socialized as a male, Nixon would not be able to provide effective counseling.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rupp |first1=Shannon |title=Transsexual loses latest bid to counsel victims of rape |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/transsexual-loses-latest-bid-to-counsel-victims-of-rape/article990772/ |work=The Globe and Mail |date=8 December 2005}}</ref> The tribunal found in Nixon's favour and issued an award of $7,500.\n\nVancouver Rape Relief appealed this decision to the [[Supreme Court of British Columbia]]. In 2005 the court repealed the tribunal's verdict, ruling that the shelter is a group protected by section 41 of the [[British Columbia Human Rights Code]],<ref>[https://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/learn/resources/vancouver-rape-relief-society-v-nixon-2005-bcca-601-summary-decision \"Vancouver Rape Relief Society v. Nixon 2005 BCCA 601 Summary of Decision\"]. 1 January 2005.</ref> which offers an exemption to certain types of organization.{{efn|[[British Columbia Human Rights Code]]: \"If a charitable, philanthropic, educational, fraternal, religious or social organization or corporation that is not operated for profit has as a primary purpose the promotion of the interests and welfare of an identifiable group or class of persons characterized by a physical or mental disability or by a common race, religion, age, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity or expression, marital status, political belief, colour, ancestry or place of origin, that organization or corporation must not be considered to be contravening this Code because it is granting a preference to members of the identifiable group or class of persons.\"<ref>[http://www.bclaws.ca/Recon/document/ID/freeside/00_96210_01#section41 \"Human Rights Code\"]. bclaws.ca.</ref>}} Nixon appealed that decision to the [[Supreme Court of Canada]], which declined to hear the appeal in February 2007.<ref>[https://www.scc-csc.ca/case-dossier/info/dock-regi-eng.aspx?cas=31633 ''Kimberly Nixon v. Vancouver Rape Relief Society'']. Supreme Court of Canada.</ref> Vancouver Rape Relief's lawyer, Christine Boyle, applauded the decision, saying that the \"right to organize has been confirmed and is under protection of the law\". Nixon's attorney, barbara findlay{{efn|findlay spells her name without capitals.<ref>{{cite web|last1=findlay|first1=barbara|title=About Me|url=http://www.barbarafindlay.com/about-me.html|website=barbara findlay Q.C.|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>}}, said she was disappointed with the ruling, but optimistic about the long-term: \"Ultimately, what is accessible to all women will be accessible to trans women, too... I think this just shows that achieving equality will take a long time for the transgendered {{sic}}. But there will be other cases.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Transsexual Loses Fight with Women's Shelter |first=Shannon |last=Rupp |newspaper=[[The Tyee]] |date=3 February 2007 |url=https://thetyee.ca/News/2007/02/03/Nixon/}}</ref>\n\nVancouver City Council pulled its funding from the organization in March 2019, after complaints from transgender activists over its policy of housing only female-born women in its shelter.<ref>[https://globalnews.ca/news/5071122/vancouver-rape-relief-and-womens-shelter-funding-trans-women]'Canada\u2019s oldest rape crisis centre faces backlash over excluding trans women' in Global News</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Radical feminism]]\n* [[Abolition of Prostitution]]\n* [[Women-only space]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter}}\n[[Category:Anti-prostitution feminism]]\n[[Category:Feminism in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Radical feminism]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in Canada]]\n[[Category:Women-only spaces]]\n[[Category:Women's organizations based in Canada]]\n[[Category:Women's shelters]]\n[[Category:Women in British Columbia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n|name         = \n|image        = Vancouver Rape Relief logo.jpeg\n|image_border =\n|size         = 300px\n|map          =\n|msize        =\n|malt         =\n|mcaption     =\n|abbreviation =\n|motto        = \"No woman is free until all women are free.\"\n|formation    = 1973\n|extinction   =\n|type         = [[Rape crisis center]]\n|status       =\n|purpose      =\n|headquarters = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]\n|location     =\n|coords       =\n|region_served = Vancouver\n|membership   =\n|language     =\n|leader_title =\n|leader_name  =\n|main_organ   =\n|parent_organization =\n|affiliations =\n|num_staff    =\n|num_volunteers =\n|budget       =\n|website      = {{URL|http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/}}\n|remarks      =\n}}\n\n'''Vancouver Rape Relief & Women's Shelter''' is Canada's oldest [[rape crisis center]], located in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Steacy |first1=Lisa |title=Opinion: Vancouver Rape Relief stands by women |url=https://vancouversun.com/opinion/vancouver-rape-relief-stands-by-women |work=Vancouver Sun |date=13 April 2016}}</ref> The shelter was established in 1973 and has operated a [[feminist]] [[Transitional living|transition house]] since 1983, offering women shelter from men who are abusing them, including fathers, husbands, sons, [[pimp]]s, johns and landlords.{{efn|\"Since 1973 the Vancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter has been an organizing centre and a 24-hour phone line for women raped and battered. Since 1980, it has also been a feminist transition house. We house women running from abusive men&nbsp;\u2013 usually husbands and fathers, but sometimes pimps, johns, landlords, and sons.\"<ref name=Lakemanp210>{{cite book |last1=Lakeman |first1=Lee |last2=Lee |first2=Alice |last3=Jay |first3=Suzanne |editor1-last=Stark |editor1-first=Christine |editor2-last=Whisnant |editor2-first=Rebecca |editor1-link= |editor2-link= |title=Not for Sale: Feminists Resisting Prostitution and Pornography |date=2004 |publisher=Spinifex Press Pty Ltd. |location=North Melbourne, Victoria |page=210 |chapter=Resisting the promotion of prostitution in Canada: A view from the Vancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter|ref=harv}}</ref>}} A member of the Canadian Association of Sexual Assault Centres (CASAC),{{sfn|Lakeman|Lee|Jay|2004|pp=210\u2013211}} it is an independent, non-governmental group with no connection to the criminal justice system.<ref>{{cite news|title=About Us |url=http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/about |accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n\n==Services==\nThe group operates a 24-hour, confidential, free-of-charge [[crisis hotline]] for abused women. More broadly, it works to eradicate all [[violence against women]], which it defines as including \"[[sexual assault]], [[domestic violence|wife assault]], [[incest]], [[prostitution]], and [[sexual harassment]]\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Give/Get Help |url=http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/givegethelp |accessdate= December 20, 2012}}</ref> According to its website, this mission is accomplished by not only providing housing, education, resources, and support for women, but also by participating in global political struggles around issues of [[Race (human classification)|race]], [[Social class|class]], [[colonialism]], and [[imperialism]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Global Resistance |url=http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/globalresistance |accessdate= December 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nVancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter consists of 27 collective members who work at the shelter, ten of whom are staff. They are committed to having their membership represent Vancouver population and therefore have a third of women identifying as lesbian women, a third are working class women, and almost half of them identify as women of colour. Vancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter have stated publicly that their collective members are themselves survivors of male violence against women, ex-callers calling the line, ex-residents who lived at the shelter, and survivors of prostitution. <ref name=Lakemanp210/>\n\n==''Kimberly Nixon v. Vancouver Rape Relief Society''==\n{{further|Kimberly Nixon Rape Relief Case}}\nIn August 1995 Kimberly Nixon, a [[trans woman]], filed a complaint against the shelter with the [[British Columbia Human Rights Tribunal]] after being turned down for a place on the shelter's training programme for volunteer counselors. Nixon argued that this constituted illegal [[discrimination]] under Section 41 of the [[British Columbia Human Rights Code]]. Vancouver Rape Relief countered that individuals are shaped by the [[socialization]] and experiences of their formative years, and that, having been socialized as a male, Nixon would not be able to provide effective counseling.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rupp |first1=Shannon |title=Transsexual loses latest bid to counsel victims of rape |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/transsexual-loses-latest-bid-to-counsel-victims-of-rape/article990772/ |work=The Globe and Mail |date=8 December 2005}}</ref> The tribunal found in Nixon's favour and issued an award of $7,500.\n\nVancouver Rape Relief appealed this decision to the [[Supreme Court of British Columbia]]. In 2005 the court repealed the tribunal's verdict, ruling that the shelter is a group protected by section 41 of the [[British Columbia Human Rights Code]],<ref>[https://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/learn/resources/vancouver-rape-relief-society-v-nixon-2005-bcca-601-summary-decision \"Vancouver Rape Relief Society v. Nixon 2005 BCCA 601 Summary of Decision\"]. 1 January 2005.</ref> which offers an exemption to certain types of organization.{{efn|[[British Columbia Human Rights Code]]: \"If a charitable, philanthropic, educational, fraternal, religious or social organization or corporation that is not operated for profit has as a primary purpose the promotion of the interests and welfare of an identifiable group or class of persons characterized by a physical or mental disability or by a common race, religion, age, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity or expression, marital status, political belief, colour, ancestry or place of origin, that organization or corporation must not be considered to be contravening this Code because it is granting a preference to members of the identifiable group or class of persons.\"<ref>[http://www.bclaws.ca/Recon/document/ID/freeside/00_96210_01#section41 \"Human Rights Code\"]. bclaws.ca.</ref>}} Nixon appealed that decision to the [[Supreme Court of Canada]], which declined to hear the appeal in February 2007.<ref>[https://www.scc-csc.ca/case-dossier/info/dock-regi-eng.aspx?cas=31633 ''Kimberly Nixon v. Vancouver Rape Relief Society'']. Supreme Court of Canada.</ref> Vancouver Rape Relief's lawyer, Christine Boyle, applauded the decision, saying that the \"right to organize has been confirmed and is under protection of the law\". Nixon's attorney, barbara findlay{{efn|findlay spells her name without capitals.<ref>{{cite web|last1=findlay|first1=barbara|title=About Me|url=http://www.barbarafindlay.com/about-me.html|website=barbara findlay Q.C.|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>}}, said she was disappointed with the ruling, but optimistic about the long-term: \"Ultimately, what is accessible to all women will be accessible to trans women, too... I think this just shows that achieving equality will take a long time for the transgendered {{sic}}. But there will be other cases.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Transsexual Loses Fight with Women's Shelter |first=Shannon |last=Rupp |newspaper=[[The Tyee]] |date=3 February 2007 |url=https://thetyee.ca/News/2007/02/03/Nixon/}}</ref>\n\nVancouver City Council pulled its funding from the organization in March 2019, after complaints from transgender activists about its policy of housing only female-born women to in its shelter.<ref>[https://globalnews.ca/news/5071122/vancouver-rape-relief-and-womens-shelter-funding-trans-women]'Canada\u2019s oldest rape crisis centre faces backlash over excluding trans women' in Global News</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Radical feminism]]\n* [[Abolition of Prostitution]]\n* [[Women-only space]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rapereliefshelter.bc.ca/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vancouver Rape Relief and Women's Shelter}}\n[[Category:Anti-prostitution feminism]]\n[[Category:Feminism in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Radical feminism]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in Canada]]\n[[Category:Women-only spaces]]\n[[Category:Women's organizations based in Canada]]\n[[Category:Women's shelters]]\n[[Category:Women in British Columbia]]\n", "name_user": "Lilipo25", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eKimberly Nixon v. Vancouver Rape Relief Society:fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vancouver_Rape_Relief_%26_Women%27s_Shelter"}
